  "question": "Given the following table. X\\Y | Y=1 | Y=2 | Y=3 | $p_X(x)$; X=1 | .01 | .20 | .09 | .3; X=2 | .07 | .00 | .03 | .1; X=3 | .09 | .05 | .06 | .2; X=4 | .03 | .25 | .12 | .4; $p_Y(y)$ | .2 | .5 | .3 | 1. Find $p_{X|Y}(x|y)$ where $Y = 2$.",
  "answer": "",
  "explanation": "$p_{X|Y}(1|2) = \\frac{p_{XY}(1, 2)}{p_Y(2)} = \\frac{.2}{.5} = 0.4$; $p_{X|Y}(2|2) = \\frac{p_{XY}(2, 2)}{p_Y(2)} = \\frac{0}{.5} = 0$; $p_{X|Y}(3|2) = \\frac{p_{XY}(3, 2)}{p_Y(2)} = \\frac{.05}{.5} = 0.1$; $p_{X|Y}(4|2) = \\frac{p_{XY}(4, 2)}{p_Y(2)} = \\frac{.25}{.5} = 0.5$; $p_{X|Y}(x|2) = \\frac{p_{XY}(x, 2)}{p_Y(2)} = \\frac{0}{.5} = 0$, $x > 4$",
